definition.value: Catalysis of the transfer of a solute or solutes from one side of a membrane to the other according to the reaction -  lactate (out) + H+ (out) -eq- lactate (in) + H+ (in).

label.value: quaternary ammonium group transmembrane transporter activity

definition.value: Catalysis of the transfer of quaternary ammonium groups from one side of a membrane to the other. Quaternary ammonium groups are any compound that can be regarded as derived from ammonium hydroxide or an ammonium salt by replacement of all four hydrogen atoms of the NH4+ ion by organic groups.

label.value: quaternary ammonium group - proton symporter activity

definition.value: Catalysis of the transfer of a solute or solutes from one side of a membrane to the other according to the reaction -  quaternary ammonium group(out) + H+(out) -eq- quaternary ammonium group(in) + H+(in).
Catalysis of the transfer of a solute or solutes from one side of a membrane to the other according to the reaction -  glycine betaine(out) + H+(out) -eq- glycine betaine(in) + H+(in).
Catalysis of the transfer of tellurite from the outside of a cell to the inside across a membrane -  tellurite(out) + H+(out) -eq- tellurite(in) + H+(in).
Catalysis of the transfer of a solute or solutes from one side of a membrane to the other according to the reaction -  alanine(out) + Na+(out) -eq- alanine(in) + Na+(in).

label.value: branched-chain amino acid - sodium symporter activity

definition.value: Catalysis of the transfer of a solute or solutes from one side of a membrane to the other according to the reaction -  branched-chain amino acid(out) + cation(out) -eq- branched-chain amino acid(in) + cation(in).

label.value: branched-chain amino acid transmembrane transporter activity

definition.value: Catalysis of the transfer of branched-chain amino acids from one side of a membrane to the other. Branched-chain amino acids are amino acids with a branched carbon skeleton without rings.
Catalysis of the transfer of formate from the outside of a cell to the inside of the cell across a membrane.
Catalysis of the transfer of formate from the inside of the cell to the outside of the cell across a membrane.
Catalysis of the transfer of L-lysine from the inside of the cell to the outside of the cell across a membrane.

label.value: ATPase activity, coupled to transmembrane movement of ions, phosphorylative mechanism

definition.value: Catalysis of the transfer of a solute or solutes from one side of a membrane to the other according to the reaction -  ATP + H2O -eq- ADP + phosphate, to directly drive the transport of ions across a membrane. The reaction is characterized by the transient formation of a high-energy aspartyl-phosphoryl-enzyme intermediate.

Enables the directed movement of nicotinamide mononucleotide into, out of or within a cell, or between cells. Nicotinamide mononucleotide is a ribonucleotide in which the nitrogenous base, nicotinamide, is in beta-n-glycosidic linkage with the c-1 position of d-ribose. It is a constituent of NAD and NADP.
Catalysis of the transfer of an alcohol from one side of the membrane to the other. An alcohol is any carbon compound that contains a hydroxyl group.
Catalysis of endonucleolytic cleavage of DNA in a site-specific manner, resulting in double-strand breaks.
Catalysis of the reaction -  S-adenosyl-L-methionine + DNA cytosine -eq- S-adenosyl-L-homocysteine + DNA N4-methylcytosine.

Catalysis of the endonucleolytic cleavage of DNA to give double-stranded fragments with terminal 5'-phosphates. ATP hydrolysis is required. Cleavage is dependent on the presence of two copies of a specific recognition sequence in an inverse orientation in the DNA. Cleavage occurs at a specific distance from one of the recognition sites.
Catalysis of the reaction -  aspartate + O2 -eq- iminosuccinate + hydrogen peroxide.
Catalysis of the hydrolysis of mannosyl compounds, substances containing a group derived from a cyclic form of mannose or a mannose derivative.
Catalysis of the hydrolysis of the terminal alpha-D-mannose residues in oligo-mannose oligosaccharides.
Catalysis of the hydrolysis of galactosyl compounds, substances containing a group derived from a cyclic form of galactose or a galactose derivative.
Catalysis of the hydrolysis of glucosyl compounds, substances containing a group derived from a cyclic form of glucose or a glucose derivative.
Catalysis of the hydrolysis of trehalose or a trehalose derivative.
Catalysis of the hydrolysis of fucosyl compounds, substances containing a group derived from a cyclic form of fucose or a fucose derivative.
Catalysis of the cleavage of hexosamine or N-acetylhexosamine residues (e.g. N-acetylglucosamine) residues from gangliosides or other glycoside oligosaccharides.
Catalysis of the formation of L-glutamine and 2-oxoglutarate from L-glutamate, using NADH, NADPH or ferredoxin as hydrogen acceptors.
Catalysis of the transfer of nucleobases, nucleosides, nucleotides and nucleic acids from one side of a membrane to the other.
The larger of the two subunits of a ribosome. Two sites on the ribosomal large subunit are involved in translation, namely the aminoacyl site (A site) and peptidyl site (P site).
The smaller of the two subunits of a ribosome.
Catalysis of the reaction -  hydrogen sulfide + acceptor + 3 H2O -eq- sulfite + reduced acceptor.
Increases the activity of a phospholipase, an enzyme that catalyzes of the hydrolysis of a glycerophospholipid.
Increases the activity of the enzyme phospholipase A2.

A product of the fusion of the mitochondria during spermatogenesis. After the completion of meiosis the mitochondria of the spermatid collect along side the nucleus and fuse into two masses -  these wrap around each other to produce the spherical Nebenkern. During flagellum elongation the Nebenkern unfolds and the two derivatives (major and minor mitochondrial derivatives) elongate down the axoneme.
The major and minor mitochondrial derivatives are the mitochondria of the sperm tail and derive by the unfolding of the Nebenkern during flagellum elongation.

The larger of the two mitochondrial derivatives that arise by the unfolding of the Nebenkern during flagellum elongation -  the major mitochondrial derivative is ovoid and darker than the minor derivative.
The smaller of the two mitochondrial derivatives that arise by the unfolding of the Nebenkern during flagellum elongation.

A multiprotein complex that forms a strong mechanical link between the cytoskeleton and extracellular matrix -  typical of, but not confined to, muscle cells. The complex is composed of transmembrane, cytoplasmic, and extracellular proteins, including dystrophin, sarcoglycans, dystroglycan, dystrobrevins, syntrophins, sarcospan, caveolin-3, and NO synthase.

A protein complex that includes alpha- and beta-dystroglycan, which are alternative products of the same gene -  the laminin-binding component of the dystrophin-associated glycoprotein complex, providing a link between the subsarcolemmal cytoskeleton (in muscle cells) and the extracellular matrix. Alpha-dystroglycan is an extracellular protein binding to alpha-laminin and to beta-dystroglycan -  beta-dystroglycan is a transmembrane protein which binds alpha-dystroglycan and dystrophin.

A protein complex formed of four sarcoglycans plus sarcospan -  there are six known sarcoglycans -  alpha-, beta-, gamma-, delta-, epsilon- and zeta-sarcoglycan -  all are N-glycosylated single-pass transmembrane proteins. The sarcoglycan-sarcospan complex is a subcomplex of the dystrophin glycoprotein complex, and is fixed to the dystrophin axis by a lateral association with the dystroglycan complex.

A protein complex that includes alpha-, beta1-, beta2-syntrophins and syntrophin-like proteins -  the syntrophin complex binds to the second half of the carboxy-terminal domain of dystrophin -  also associates with neuronal nitric oxide synthase.
A protein complex comprising alpha- and beta-dystrobrevin -  forms part of the dystrophin glycoprotein complex.
Acts as a trigger for a pattern specification process when present at a specific concentration within a gradient.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with cyclosporin A, a cyclic undecapeptide that contains several N-methylated and unusual amino acids.
Combining with a peptidoglycan and transmitting the signal to initiate a change in cell activity.
Double layer of lipid molecules that encloses all cells, and, in eukaryotes, many organelles -  may be a single or double lipid bilayer -  also includes associated proteins.

The component of a membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that have some part that penetrates at least one leaflet of the membrane bilayer. This component includes gene products that are buried in the bilayer with no exposure outside the bilayer.
A membrane-bounded vesicle found in the cytoplasm of the cell.
A complex of proteins that are involved in phototransduction and attached to the transient receptor potential (TRP) channel. The protein connections are mediated through inaD.
The specialized microvilli-containing organelle on the apical surfaces of a photoreceptor cell containing the visual pigment rhodopsin and most of the proteins involved in phototransduction.
A membrane-bounded compartment that is found at the base of the rhabdomere and contains stored calcium, InsP3 receptors and smooth endoplasmic reticulum Ca2+-ATPase.
